\pard\sa200\sl240\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs40\lang9 #\cf0 Diet Sentry overview\par

\pard\li721\sa200\sl240\slmult1\qj\kerning2\b0\f1\fs22\lang3081 This application can assist in dieting and healthy nutrition by enabling the user to record the food they eat during the day. In particular the energy (in kJ) and a range of nutrients and ingredients.\par
\kerning0\f2\lang9 To record the eating of a food the user selects its row from the DataGrid in the <Food> tab and double clicks the mouse or presses the \{Enter\} Key. They can then enter the amount consumed in either grams or millilitres (if the food is a liquid). Once the \{Enter\} key is pressed the details of this food are copied with a time stamp to a row of the DataGrid in the <Eaten> tab to which focus is then passed.\par
The foods displayed in the DataGrid of the <Eaten> tab can then be totalled for a particular day. This shows how much energy, nutrients and ingredients where consumed in total.\par
The database of foods is quite comprehensive however the user can add new foods. The editing, detailed viewing and deleting of foods is also possible. There a three types of foods: Liquids, Solids and Recipies. \par
The foods database and units are unashamedly based on Australian standards with energy recorded in kJ and not Calories, while other quantities are measured in millilitres (mL) or grams (g) or even mg and \'b5g as appropriate. Dates are in the sensible dd-MMM-yyyy format and the time of day is based on 24 hours (not AM and PM).\par
\par

\pard\sa200\sl240\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs36 #\cf0 Foods table\par

\pard\li721\sa200\sl240\slmult1\qj\b0\f2\fs22 Each record (table row) stores details of a particular food item. In particular a text description and then energy content and amounts of various nutrients and quantities. In all cases these are based on either 100g or 100mL of the food. If the foods description ends with the characters "mL*" or "mL" the food is measured in millilitres (mL), otherwise in grams (g).\par
This table is stored in the SQLiite foods.db database distributed with this application. It can be directly examined or edited with many available applications. Eg. DB Browser for SQLite. The table is visible via a DataGrid component in the <Food> tab of the applications main form, with the assumed units visible in the headers.\par
Below are the self explanatory internal names and details of a records fields.\par

